body:
Since everyone but me has watched the new Good Omens adaptation, I thought I’d share my favourite fic rec from days of yore (aka 2003) : 

Living Arangements by afrai
Summary: Everyone is human, even when they aren’t.
Pairing: Crowley/Aziraphale

Quote from fic:
“His problem was that he’d always had hope. He’d always believes that everything would turn out more or less all right in the end, if only because it had always done so before.”

It’s probably my favourite thing I’ve read in that fandom! Mind the tags.

summary: heaven as a cold, sparse corporation is fucking incredible to me because it works so well. in the beginning, crowley says he...
body:
heaven as a cold, sparse corporation is fucking incredible to me because it works so well. in the beginning, crowley says he doesn’t see what’s so wrong with knowing the difference between good and evil and aziraphale counters that “it must be bad or you wouldn’t have tempted them into it”. but he doesn’t know either. 

he doesn’t know the difference between good and evil in this case, only what he’s been told from the higher ups. he has a list of arbitrary rules and guidelines that he’s supposed to follow, someone he’s supposed to check in with, but he doesn’t know the point of it. 

and crowley, well, crowley was always asking questions. he doesn’t accept things at face value. if it’s supposed to be bad, he wants to know why, and that’s why he fell. because heaven llc can’t have him being the squeaky wheel. they can’t have him trying to find things out. they need good little workers like aziraphale who do as their told and don’t ask why. 

but there’s a spark of rebellion in aziraphale, and crowley sees it. he sees it when aziraphale admits to giving away the flaming sword that was literally given to him by god because he was worried that adam and eve would be cold and in danger. he sees it when aziraphale opens a bookshop and takes him to little restaurants and drinks wine. when he uses miracles to fix bikes and spends 6000 years talking to him like he’s someone who matters instead of just a demon. for the most part. 

crowley thinks he’ll do anything for that spark in the angel.

summary: loving crowley terrifies aziraphale because if he loves crowley, if he accepts that crowley is wonderful and capable of giving...
body:
loving crowley terrifies aziraphale because if he loves crowley, if he accepts that crowley is wonderful and capable of giving and receiving love, then it means that his whole existence, his whole purpose, everything he’s supposed to believe is shaky at best and an outright lie at worst. because if he loves crowley, a demon, an agent of the adversary, then how can he be the good guy? how can he be holy? how can he be worthy of the almighty’s love if he’s betrayed the light so badly?

and it’s so hard because everything in him tells him that this is right and good and pure and that love can never be bad, especially when it makes him feel as good as crowley makes him feel. 

it’s confusing and he has no one to talk to about it, and so it really must be best to bury it and pretend it isn’t real and keep crowley out of trouble and try to save the world, but every time crowley smiles at him or does a ‘demonic miracle’ to help him, aziraphale slips a little bit further, and he’s so afraid of falling completely.

There is no heterosexual explanation of the last scene in which the camera pans away from Crowley and Aziraphale talking excitedly over lunch at the Ritz , and then pans to a bird at the park while the lyrics “angels dined at the Ritz and a nightingale sang at Berkeley square” play
